package upstream ver 1;
public class Point extends Object {
  private float x;
  private float y;
  public Point(float x, float y) {
    this.x = x;
    this.y = y;
  }
  public Point move(Displacement d) {
    return new Point(x + d.getValue(new Displacement(1f)), 0f);
  }

}

/*
What I want to do:
Generate constraints from method invocations/object instantiations.

There are two possibilities, the receiver is currently still written in BatakJava, or already translated
and an overview is available.

(1) Overview

If an overview is already available, for example
  float distance(Point var1) in ver 1,2,3 {
    float distance(ver1_Point var1) in ver 1 {}
    float distance(ver2_Point var1) in ver 2 {}
    float distance(ver3_Point var1) in ver 3 {}
  }
Given the variable of the receiver and arguments, we can create a map
{[recVar:1, argVar:1],[recVar:2, argVar:2],[recVar:3, argVar:3]}

(2) Batakjava

Calling decl() on the method access will return a declaration
  public Point move(Displacement d) { ... }

Given the variable of the receiver, argument, and return type, we can create
equality constraints
{[recVar = methodHostVar, argVar = methodArgVar, methodVar = methodReturnVar]}
*/